Hartlepool - a small town (Population 96,000) situated within Teesside, North East England. The origin of the name 'Hartlepool' is the subject of some conjecture, but it seems certain that 'harts'- i.e. stags or deer, and water figure strongly in it. Bede refers to it as 'the place where harts drink' and the ancient author Hutchinson, in his work on Northumberland, suggests that the name refers to the 'island of harts', which he claims was a wooded peninsula which was cut off from the mainland at high tide. Another theory suggests that the name distinguishes this particular part of the manor of Hart as being by the sea, i.e. Hart 'le-pool'.

